22/11/2006

 Bulgarian duo Albena Denkova and Maxim Staviski won the ice dance title at the Trophee Bompard event in Paris. The world champions finished with a score of 197.25 points, followed by France's Isabelle Delobel and Olivier Schoenfelder with 194.62 and Italy's Federica Faiella and Massimo Scali with 176.62. Denkova and Staviski will now participate in the season-ending Grand Prix Final in Russia next month. 
*** 
The Macedonian band "Leb i sol", one of the most popular groups of the former Yugoslavia, kicked off a big regional tour with a concert in Novi Sad. The tour -- which will run through until December 28th -- marks the 30th anniversary of the band. The group will also perform in Banja Luka, Split, Zagreb, Rijeca, Sarajevo, Skopje, Ljubljana and Belgrade. 
*** 
A giant painting created by Romanian pupils from Nicolae Tonitza High School in Bucharest has been entered in the Guinness Book of Records. The 3,464m long picture was officially measured by representatives of the Guinness Book at the Baneasa Airport, where it is being displayed. 
*** 
The 47th edition of the Thessaloniki International Film Festival opened in Thessaloniki, Greece. It runs through November 26th. Fourteen films -- two Greek and 12 foreign -- are included in the official competition section. This year, the programme also spotlights Brazilian and new Chinese cinema and offers a special retrospective of world-renowned German director Wim Wenders. 
*** 
A sculpture titled "Orpheus' Lyre" by the renowned Bulgarian artist Ziyatin Nuriev, who now lives and works in Istanbul, was formally unveiled in the centre of Kardzhali, Bulgaria. The giant statue is 9m high and 12m wide and was made with 3.6 tonnes of steel. 
*** 
The Serbian women's volleyball team won a bronze medal in the World League contest, held in Japan last week. The Serbs defeated Italy, 3-0. Russia won the gold medal and Brazil took silver. 
 (Various sources 15/11/06-22/11/06)  
